142
00:22:54.770 --> 00:22:58.779
Marcin Bugaj: A quick project… a quick update on the project tree.

143
00:22:59.270 --> 00:23:03.690
Marcin Bugaj: the KVM guest API standardization.

144
00:23:05.070 --> 00:23:08.720
Marcin Bugaj: We now have… we now have 7, standards accepted.

145
00:23:09.270 --> 00:23:13.950
Marcin Bugaj: Here's the list. One standard is in review.

146
00:23:14.070 --> 00:23:17.749
Marcin Bugaj: It has been heavily discussed, the static library and linker script.

147
00:23:18.150 --> 00:23:21.610
Marcin Bugaj: There are two new drafts,

148
00:23:21.940 --> 00:23:23.970
Marcin Bugaj: That I'll introduce in a moment.

149
00:23:26.020 --> 00:23:31.740
Marcin Bugaj: The new one, in review, defines the runtime

150
00:23:31.870 --> 00:23:36.749
Marcin Bugaj: each vendor ships. It's two things, static library and the linker script.

151
00:23:37.320 --> 00:23:44.870
Marcin Bugaj: The library holds everything the KVM-specific, the entry point, I.O, the accelerators, and early hook.

152
00:23:46.580 --> 00:23:56.829
Marcin Bugaj: The boot flow is on the right, start runs, gives the guest an optional early hook, as was requested by Nethermind.

153
00:23:57.350 --> 00:24:06.920
Marcin Bugaj: Sets up the stack and global pointer, does the vendor's own the KVM-specific setup, so that I.O. is ready.

154
00:24:07.040 --> 00:24:08.790
Marcin Bugaj: and then call Termin.

155
00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:11.779
Marcin Bugaj: The value mine returns.

156
00:24:11.990 --> 00:24:15.489
Marcin Bugaj: Besides success or all failure.

157
00:24:15.830 --> 00:24:21.980
Marcin Bugaj: There was one open question during review, how a guest takes ownership of the hip.

158
00:24:22.500 --> 00:24:32.459
Marcin Bugaj: And we landed on a simple approach. Two standard symbols, heap start and heap end, are exported by the linker script, and the ownership

159
00:24:32.680 --> 00:24:39.720
Marcin Bugaj: the sole ownership over, HIP is taken by, the guest program.

160
00:24:40.630 --> 00:24:51.509
Marcin Bugaj: The update is that ZISK has agreed to that proposal, so, this proposal is moving toward March, hopefully next week.

161
00:24:53.110 --> 00:24:57.790
Marcin Bugaj: The first new draft is about loading the program.

162
00:24:58.320 --> 00:25:02.420
Marcin Bugaj: The guest executable is shipped as an ELF file.

163
00:25:02.600 --> 00:25:15.410
Marcin Bugaj: And the ELF format is flexible, and today, different ZKVMs load ELF files in slightly different ways. What the standard pins down is the interpretation of ELF.

164
00:25:15.760 --> 00:25:23.599
Marcin Bugaj: It gives one precise, deterministic way to turn it into the initial state of the RISC-V machine.

165
00:25:23.810 --> 00:25:30.429
Marcin Bugaj: It does that by disambiguating two choices that CKVMs made differently.

166
00:25:30.770 --> 00:25:36.949
Marcin Bugaj: The first is where the loaded image actually comes from.

167
00:25:37.320 --> 00:25:41.729
Marcin Bugaj: An elf describes its contents in two places.

168
00:25:41.890 --> 00:25:44.360
Marcin Bugaj: The program header and the section header.

169
00:25:44.620 --> 00:25:53.079
Marcin Bugaj: And right now, some ZKVMs read one, and some read the other, so the very same file could…

170
00:25:53.310 --> 00:25:59.749
Marcin Bugaj: potentially produce different memory content depending on the interpretation.

171
00:25:59.950 --> 00:26:13.160
Marcin Bugaj: The standard settles this on the program headers, and that's exactly what they are for. It's also what real RISC-V hardware and hardware in general, and emulators already use.

172
00:26:13.360 --> 00:26:18.360
Marcin Bugaj: One nice consequence is that, if a binary is stripped from,

173
00:26:18.720 --> 00:26:29.029
Marcin Bugaj: for example, from section headers, from other unnecessary metadata, then the ELF will, still load correctly.

174
00:26:29.420 --> 00:26:34.620
Marcin Bugaj: The second is what I'll call, the code as data problem.

175
00:26:34.780 --> 00:26:39.770
Marcin Bugaj: Some ZKVMs transpile the program's code into their own internal form.

176
00:26:40.100 --> 00:26:48.440
Marcin Bugaj: And that breaks when data is embedded in the code, like JAMP tables, the compiler,

177
00:26:48.630 --> 00:26:50.980
Marcin Bugaj: Could place next to the instructions.

178
00:26:51.320 --> 00:26:56.689
Marcin Bugaj: The standard fixes this by keeping code and treat-only data in separate segments.

179
00:26:57.260 --> 00:27:00.729
Marcin Bugaj: It's a compiler thing, but,

180
00:27:01.560 --> 00:27:11.129
Marcin Bugaj: it's mostly controlled by, the way script… linker script is written, so the, standard mandates that,

181
00:27:11.380 --> 00:27:17.660
Marcin Bugaj: The linker script, separates the executable section, which…

182
00:27:18.120 --> 00:27:21.980
Marcin Bugaj: Must not contain anything but, instructions.

183
00:27:23.250 --> 00:27:30.989
Marcin Bugaj: On top of that, the loader validates the ELF metadata, making sure that a file is really the kind

184
00:27:31.260 --> 00:27:35.290
Marcin Bugaj: of, of program this KPM can run.

185
00:27:35.480 --> 00:27:39.749
Marcin Bugaj: An invite ELF is required to be rejected up front.

186
00:27:39.970 --> 00:27:45.100
