360
00:52:21.830 --> 00:52:34.250
ben: Default allocator is not freeing, and as a result for this, I was able to fix 13 of these tests that were up to 60 million gas.

361
00:52:34.360 --> 00:52:44.259
ben: And then I looked into, some continuation of work from previous month, which was more on optimization of the…

362
00:52:44.410 --> 00:52:46.120
ben: Guest program.

363
00:52:46.560 --> 00:52:52.689
ben: So, the first change, that I did, which is already merged.

364
00:52:52.990 --> 00:53:04.839
ben: better uses the memory that is allocated in the call frame in ethrex. This is not a problem in the standard execution model, and the allocator handles this optimally.

365
00:53:05.020 --> 00:53:19.879
ben: However, in the ZKVM, we need to reuse it, and this was, able to clear up around 11 of the failing tests, and then the second case…

366
00:53:20.180 --> 00:53:29.999
ben: This was a… this was a special… special fixture that was targeting contracts that were full of job instructions.

367
00:53:30.090 --> 00:53:41.709
ben: And I changed encoding instead of the indices of the jump destinations into a bit vector. This is already an approach that is used by REF and GEF.

368
00:53:41.920 --> 00:53:54.960
ben: And this was able to fix the… fix the tests, and also uses around 10% less memory on the average maintenance blocks, but depends on which block you take, look. Some of them used more.

369
00:53:55.980 --> 00:54:00.000
ben: And then, in the third PR, I…

370
00:54:00.460 --> 00:54:17.300
ben: did a refactor of the codebase such that almost all of the hash function calls that are in the guest program are now routed through the precompiles to the respective ZKVM instead of the software implementation.

371
00:54:18.130 --> 00:54:25.540
ben: So, this produces speedup at around 1.5% of the mainnet blocks that I tested.

372
00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:38.469
ben: And then, in the following PR, I did a continuation of the previous work on serialization for the execution witness.

373
00:54:38.470 --> 00:54:47.919
ben: So now, the tree is not encoded recursively, but instead, we encode flat notes using SSD.

374
00:54:48.060 --> 00:55:02.640
ben: And this aligns closer with the specification that we have, but we also need to keep in mind that this is slightly more complicated, and the guests also need to reconstruct the tree.

375
00:55:03.630 --> 00:55:15.820
ben: And as for the final work, I looked into a paper that was recently presented at the ZK Proof Rome on evaluating the compiler optimization impacts.

376
00:55:16.310 --> 00:55:19.670
ben: And here I tried…

377
00:55:20.460 --> 00:55:37.679
ben: different, different options to… to speed up the guest program, and I limited myself to only adjusting the arguments and not doing any patches to LLVM. So we agreed that to keep the LLVM standardized and not change the compiler.

378
00:55:38.050 --> 00:55:48.969
ben: And with applying an optimizer to the arguments, I was able to get around 10.5% improvement with no changes to the source code.

379
00:55:49.120 --> 00:55:57.680
ben: Which is… which is pretty decent. And I also have my write-up, which you can check, I will send the link to the chat.

