397
00:57:25.670 --> 00:57:32.970
Derek Sorensen: If you don't have context, EVM ASM is an assembly-level implementation of the EVM.

398
00:57:33.130 --> 00:57:40.340
Derek Sorensen: in lean, we're doing it for a few reasons, including

399
00:57:40.470 --> 00:57:51.719
Derek Sorensen: possible big wins in efficiency, using formal verification, and, and so we can… the idea is that we can,

400
00:57:52.150 --> 00:57:55.889
Derek Sorensen: kind of pin, Gen AI between

401
00:57:56.180 --> 00:58:06.900
Derek Sorensen: two formal specs. One of them is of RISC-V, and the other of the EVM, and have it write assembly directly. And then we can extract… we can… we can…

402
00:58:07.730 --> 00:58:25.809
Derek Sorensen: get this RISC-V and put it in an ELF and run it in ZKVMs in the wild. So that's the idea. I'll give an update on… on three kind of levels, on the EVM opcode, level, then the state transition function, and the code gem.

403
00:58:26.110 --> 00:58:35.259
Derek Sorensen: So… Currently, we have 110 opcodes that have… that run, they have formal specs, they have formal proofs.

404
00:58:35.420 --> 00:58:42.119
Derek Sorensen: These are the, kind of, most basic ones, arithmetic, bitwise, shifts, comparisons, byte, stack family.

405
00:58:43.450 --> 00:58:54.259
Derek Sorensen: We have, almost all of the other opcodes are at varying stages of executable and able to kind of extract and run in their own environment.

406
00:58:54.380 --> 00:59:01.019
Derek Sorensen: And they're a little bit more complicated, so these include mol mod, SMOD, X, etc.

407
00:59:01.560 --> 00:59:07.269
Derek Sorensen: There are only 3 opcodes that have not been done yet, and these are the Cancun ones, so they're kind of on…

408
00:59:07.330 --> 00:59:22.110
Derek Sorensen: On the to-do list… to-do list. So we have, we can formally prove, these opcodes correct with regards to a spec, and we can also extract most of them, and run them in,

409
00:59:22.250 --> 00:59:32.519
