444
01:04:34.010 --> 01:04:38.809
Peter: So maybe just a quick, quick context for those of you who might not be familiar with this EIP.

445
01:04:38.990 --> 01:04:42.110
Peter: The idea is that once we have ZK testers.

446
01:04:42.370 --> 01:05:00.379
Peter: well, our testers can attest without downloading the payload, so we don't have this implicit data availability guarantee anymore. That might be an issue. So, what is suggested here is that we take the payloads, we encode it into one or more blobs, and then use the existing data availability,

447
01:05:00.660 --> 01:05:06.520
Peter: functionality of Ethereum to ensure that the data is available for anyone to download and re-execute if they want.

448
01:05:06.680 --> 01:05:12.470
Peter: So, this is orthogonal to 8025, but… Quite related to it.

449
01:05:12.680 --> 01:05:19.080
Peter: There's two variants. There's a native variant, and there's a KBM variant, so the native variant is, in the EL.

450
01:05:19.210 --> 01:05:22.310
Peter: So, from the engine API perspective, when we produce the payloads.

451
01:05:22.460 --> 01:05:34.719
Peter: We do an additional step of encoding the payload into blobs, and then we pass these blobs to the CL, and we also set the number of the blobs in the block header, or the payload header.

452
01:05:35.390 --> 01:05:37.759
Peter: And in the ZK variant.

453
01:05:38.260 --> 01:05:51.509
Peter: When we produce the payloads and the witness, we also produce KZG commitments and proofs for these payload blobs, and in the gas program, during proving, we verified these proofs.

454
01:05:51.900 --> 01:05:54.710
Peter: So that's kind of the high-level idea. I've been working on…

